VAN, CHARLES JORDAN\nDECORATING STANDING COMMITTEE\nManufacturers -ROBERT DIETZ, Sr.. MARGARET PARKER. RAY\nBROOKES\nOperatives JAMES SLAVEN, THO& WOOD, ROLAND HORTON\nELECTION IN THE U. S. S. R.\nA FEW Sundays ago the U. S. S. R. held its first\nnational election in eight years. Premier\nJoseph Stalin was a candidate for the Soviet Par\nliament The election was a simple matter. Only\none party participated. Only one candidate had\nbeen nominated for each office. The election was\nthe occasion for expressions of gratification at the\ngains of the U. S. S. R. and for speeches by candi\ndates. In the speechmaking and victory celebra\ntions there was nothing to indicate that victory\nover the Axis was the result of the cooperation of\nthree great powers and that huge war supplies\nhad been furnished the Red Army from outside\nthe U. S. S. R.\nMr. Molotov said:\n\u201cWe have defeated a most dangerous enemy,\nhave achieved a glorious victory, still further\nconsolidated the family of the Soviet nations and\nraised to unprecedented heights the authority of\nthe Soviet Union.\u2019\u2019\nMr. Malenkow declared:\n\u201cOur friends will respect us only so long as\nWe are strong. The weak are not respected.\u201d\nAll gloried in the strength of the Red Army.\nMost important of all was the election speech\nof Premier Stalin broadcast from Moscow.\nStalin also made force the keynote of his speech\nin relating Russia\u2019s victory in the war and her\nprogress in communizing the industrial and\nagricultural resources of the country. He an\nnounced that a fourth Five-Year Plan will\ndevelop still further the heavy industries\u2014steel,\noil, pig-iron, coal. Clearly, the Communist Party\nis planning power for Soviet states, with no con\ncem for the responsibility that is involved in\nthat power.\nAll of this emphasis on power and the heavy\nindustries, with an army of 15,000,OO^f-under\narms, makes \u201cPower for what?\u201d the obvious\nquestion. The secret police has been an effective\npride. The rights of individual citizens are no\nagency in which the Communist Party takes\nmore secure in Russia now than under the czars.\nAll of these plans to expand economic facili\nties, scientific research, increase production 30\nper cent, etc., will strengthen the great police\nstate, but there is no word to indicate that that\ngreat nation is seeking to promote human wel\nfare or base human relations on principles of\nmoral justice. It is a great pity that Russia\ncontinues to think in terms that most nations have\nlearned are futile.\nFULL EMPLOYMENT LEGISLATION\nTpULL employment\u2014jobs for all who are able to\nwork and who want them-\u2014cannot be estab\nlished by passing a law. All that the law can do\nis set up a policy toward which governpient\nagencies may work. That, apparently, is what the\nnew measure which was signed a few days ago\nby President Truman, will do. How successful\nwe may be in eliminating unemployment will de\npend upon the manner in which the policy of full\nemployment is put into effect by government.\nThe new act not only declares it to le the\nnational policy to promote jobs for all, it also\npledges the government \u201cto coordinate and utilize\nall its plans, functions, and resources for the pur\npose of creating and maintaining useful em\nployment opjiortunities, including self employ\nment, for those able, w illing, and seeking to work,\nand to promote maximum employment, production\nand purchasing power.\u201d It requires the President\nto tell Congress every year how many jobs will lie\nrequired in order to attain the goal of full cm\n4 ployment. It also sets up machinery for planning,\n*and provides for the apixiintment of a council of\neconomic advisers to help the President. Joint\ne committees of Congress will study recommenda\ntions received from the President and coordinate\nactiqa upon them to carry out the purpose of the\nn That, briefly, is the new federal statute on\nemployment. It does not set up a great program\nof federal works, it merely provides for getting\nthe facts and making recommendations to Con\ngress. After that, it is up to the lawmakers te\nmake the whole idea work.\nThe full employment statute is a long st\nin the right direction. It preserves our American\nway of life it does not provide for a system ol\nsocialism. It sets up for the first time in our his\ntory a national policy of jobs for all who can and\nwant to work,\n*v\n\u2022\u2014-?y\nY.\nOUR FOREIGN POLICY\nTN THE United States we have a way of lift I\nthat accepts the dignity of each human being I\nand accords each the rights inherent in that I\ndignity. We Americans value this way of lift I\nso highly that we are unwilling to make anj I\ncompromise that would alter this basic principle I\nIn the past we have been able to maintain ou: I\nchosen way of life free from outside interference I\nBut the world has been drawn closer together I\nuntil now, as a basis for self-preservation, we art I\ntrying to create a United Nations Organizatior I\nthrough which we can reach agreements or I\naction as well as deal with matters which I\nthreaten peace between nations. I\nAs these United Nations agencies get intc I \u2018r\u00ae\noperation, they must make decisions on prac I ^at\ntically every issue either in accord With th( I\ndemocratic way Of life or favor Of author! I\ntarian principles. I\nAt London, in the recent deliberations\nUNO S General Assembly and Security Council I n\nthere were proposals that sought to take prestigf I\nfrom democratic countries in order to provid I\nsafety for the political and economic system O\ntho USSR Grpat Britain waq\nme u. p. o.\nk.\nHip\nmost of the attacks. It was a matter of grea I\nregret to us that our government representative I\nWhile we realize the importance OI mediation\nbetween clashing interests, it is not wise or saf( I\nfor US to content ourselves with that positioi I\n-a. kt a*\na* i\nto administer even-handed justice and in accorc\nwith democratic principles. In the period n I\nwhich the United Nations agencies are organiz I\ning and gaining authority, many problems mus' I ng\u2019\nwait solution in order to escape decisions worse\nthan present conditions. I\nOur foreign policy should safeguard our wa?\nof life at home by strengthening and reinforcing k\nnations with similar tastes and ways so that inter I\nnational decisions will not restrict them. Th(\nhave crippled her for the present an oppor-\ntunity welcomed by an aggressor nation. Ir\nappreciation of the lone fight Britain made I\nagainst Hitler and the political institutions b}\nand (2) adopt a forceful and positive foreign!\npolicy of putting our full support back of demo-r\ncratic principles and nations that support demo\ncratic practices.\nThe economic recovery of Great Britain will\nmean increased strength for democratic institu\ntions. Our wealth and political influence should\nbe utilized to help other countries with demo\ncratic institutions, so that expanding production\nwill bring greater comforts to all shouldering\nthe responsibilities of world trade.\nnomic indenendence\ni ?i\nOut* fniliirp tn qfand bv Iran resulted in thel\ncompiomise which Wil inevitably make her a handed down\nfriendly nation, railure to suppoib unineseiotber\nrights in Manchuria will endanger China\u2019s eco-lprotection\na\nas me saying guea.\nFailure to take a strong!ers-\nlarge areas for decades. I\nOur foreign policy should consistently support!Workers\nlaboi these days ot advancing wage scales *DiaiaiS0 ^oo\nother conditions ot employment, cost oi living,\nflation. etc., but vou \u201cain\u2019t heard nothing\nas the saving goes You haven\u2019t even been toldlact.\niuu\n1OW much the cost of living really has advanced. I\nAnd then there is among employers and busi-L\nness men almost universal condemnation of labor\nunion \u201croyalties and other new concessions now\nbeing demanded. In Congress a bill has been\ntroduced to curb one union\nsources of information, both-printed and on the!\nair. The only real information vou can expect will!\nDe a laixir newspapti.\nnow, for many years the steel business exacted I\na royalty in the form of what was known\nto its cost in Pittsburgh plus transportation,I\nThese are only two instances of the control\nbusiness exercises over your existence. Others\ncould be cited, but it all comes back to the fact\nthat labor, in demanding some of the gravy is\nmerely imitating the methods of big business.\nFOR PERSONAL VEGEANCE\n11ECAUSE some members of the House and\nSenate didn\u2019t like the way James Petrillo,\npresident of the Musicians International Union\nparted his hair, or because he did not kow-tow\nproperly, they are wrecking their personal ven\ngeance upon him by passing a specially hateful\nanti-union law which makes it a crime, punishable\nby imprisonment in a federal penitentiary, for\nUnion men to talk about striking for higher wages.\nYes, that is the supreme limit to which small\nminded men will go. That such members fall far\nshort of the type of statesmanship this country\n\u2022needs in Congress, goes without saying.\nlawyers versed in such things say the bill\nis unconstitutional and cannot be enforced. That,\nhowever, isn\u2019t the question. It was passed by men\nwho should be alxye petty personal acts of re\nvenge against individuals. Yes, our Congress hit\na new low in lawmaking.\nBut vou hear nothing' about business roval-1(ordhe?iE,eare\n^ay hSve been.in the\nFor instance, though it has been abolished\nwhich brought steel made on the west coast up to life\nthe Pittsburgh price.\nAnd there is oleomargarine. Puttermakers\nhave for many years been able to persuade you to\nuse their product by' having federal and state\ngovernment exact taxes which brings the price\nof oleo to just about what butter sells for. And\neven then you can\u2019t buy it already colored.\n....U' \u2018\"I-1\nTHE POTTERS HERALD\n,w i\nTTNTn\u00bb\u00ab r\u2014i ..--i I he FCC with a ridic